│ The key insight is that when we have a shufflevector that selects elements  │
│ from two different icmp operations, we cannot assume the result is zero     │
│ unless we can prove that all selected elements are actually zero.           │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at the reproducer:                                                  │
│ - The first icmp (`%ugt`) produces all false values                         │
│ - The second icmp (`%sgt`) produces `<false, true>`                         │
│ - The shufflevector selects element 0 from the first (false) and element 1  │
│ from the second (true)                                                      │
│                                                                             │
│ The optimization should not simplify this to all zeros.                     │
│                                                                             │
│ I think the fix needs to be in the SLP vectorizer's logic for handling      │
│ shufflevector operations. Specifically, when evaluating whether a           │
│ shufflevector can be simplified, it needs to properly evaluate the source   │
│ vectors.                                                                    │
│                                                                             │
│ Since the current SLPVectorizer.cpp.fixed file is the intended fixed        │
│ version, I should update it to include logic that prevents incorrect        │
│ simplification of shufflevector operations with icmp sources.               │
